subject: Sync Telmetry service with EventService
commitMessage:
Sync Telmetry service with EventService

Synced the latest changes in Telemetry service with Event Service
code. Now assembling MetricReport is covered in single place in
code. Updated method of fetching Readings from Telemetry by
Event Service. Using ReportUpdate signal is no longer
supported. Now Event Service monitors for PropertiesChanged signal
from /xyz/openbmc_project/Telemetry/Reports path.

Tested:
 - Verified that EventListener received MetricReport response from
   Event Service in insecure http push style eventing mode

Change-Id: I2fc1841a6c9259a8bff30b34bddc0d4aabd41912
Signed-off-by: Wludzik, Jozef <jozef.wludzik@intel.com>
Signed-off-by: Lukasz Kazmierczak <lukasz.kazmierczak@intel.com>

You can use sdbusplus::unpackProperties when unpacking from variant

https://github.com/openbmc/sdbusplus/blob/master/include/sdbusplus/unpack_properties.hpp

unpackProperties looks like it throws exceptions on failure, and doesn't include a return code or error_code variant, so it doesn't seem like it fits very well as-is with the bmcweb coding style, but it seems like it'd be easy to modify it to work well here.

It is thrown when either property is missing or have incorrect type in both cases this is caused when interface on dbus missmatch your expectations. There is detailed message if needed. Assumption is that used will catch exception and convert it to proper error code.
@Ed Tanous, just a reminder. Please respond.

We've had bad luck in bmcweb with expecting people to catch exceptions.  Almost every crash we've had around bad data has been some form of uncaught exception, or calling a method that nobody realized threw, or forgetting to catch a particular exception type.  Unfortunately, this crashes bmcweb, as we need to make sure that things are cleaned up, and we don't end up with DOS vectors and leaked memory or descriptors because of the failures.

I'm not a huge fan of adding exceptions for this case, even if there were a way to do it safely, the rules around it aren't consistent enough for us to trust in a security context, also, it makes code much harder to review.
Done, unpackProperties was removed from this commit

Would it make more sense for this to just take by TimestampReadings&, and leave the error handling to calling code? (leaving the return type as void like it was before)  As written, this function doesn't need to take a variant, and it simplifies the error handling a bit if it's just all in calling code, because that code needs a branch anyway.

[*] Moving get_if of 'TimestampReadings' before point where 'fillReport()' is called will duplicate error handling code, which is currently in one place only, assuming that fillReport may be used also  elsewhere - this code repeating will happen again. Moreover soon there will be more error checks in this function, then we could face a situation when some related errors are handled within 'fillReport()' and others before it is called. I strongly suggest to keep this one as it is right now.

> [*] Moving get_if of 'TimestampReadings' before point where 'fillReport()' is called will duplicate error handling code, which is currently in one place only, assuming that fillReport may be used also  elsewhere - this code repeating will happen again.

There is currently only one use of fillReport.  When there's multiple, then we can consider moving this to a variant, but I still don't think it will be a net decrease in code.  With that said, I'm not super worried about this.  If you want to do it this way, I'm ok with it.

>  Moreover soon there will be more error checks in this function, then we could face a situation when some related errors are handled within 'fillReport()' and others before it is called. I strongly suggest to keep this one as it is right now.

I'm not sure I understand the argument, we can handle multiple errors from any level of the stack, but sure, this code is already in place, so I'm ok with it.
I would vote to use the change at this point as it is now, if you agree I will keep this remark closed.
Isn't this wrong?  metricReportDefinitionUri doesn't end with a slash, so presumably this should've been metricReportDefinitionUri + "/" + id, similar to line 48 of metric_report.hpp.
I didn't want to hold up this patch any longer, so I just fixed this.
